-- South African Stocks: Anglo, Avusa, Billiton, Ellies, SABMiller
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-18T16:30:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-18/south-african-stocks-advance-led-by-anglo-american-bhp-billiton-and-sab.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  snapped two days of declines, adding 228.83, or 0.7
percent, to 31,574 by the 5 p.m. in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, rallied 4.74 rand, or 1.5 percent, to 326.99 rand, the
first increase in three days. Copper rose for a second day in
New York and London as the dollar weakened, spurring demand for
commodities as an alternative investment, on the prospect of a
European Union-led bailout for Ireland. Lead, tin, nickel and
zinc all advanced.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, climbed the most in more than a week, adding 3.62 rand,
or 1.4 percent, to 262.85 rand.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ), Africa’s largest gold
mining company, rallied for the first day in five, rising 2.30
rand, or 0.7 percent, to 337.49 rand. The company resumed work
at its Mponeng mine in South Africa after the body of a missing
worker was found. Gold advanced as much as 1.7 percent to
$1,358.81.  Avusa Ltd.  (AVU SJ), the media company that owns Business
Day newspaper, increased for the second day, adding 63 cents, or
2.8 percent, to 22.79 rand. Profit climbed to 63 million rand in
the six months through September compared with 53 million rand
a year earlier.  Barloworld Ltd.  (BAW SJ), the world’s largest forklift
dealer, advanced to the highest since November 2008, gaining
1.24 rand, or 2.2 percent, to 56.50 rand. Deutsche Bank AG
industrial analyst  Roy Mutooni  raised the shares to “hold,”
from “sell.”  Ellis Holdings Ltd.  (ELI SJ), the manufacturer of satellite
television equipment, snapped two days of losses, rising 4
cents, or 2.4 percent, to 1.68 rand. Ellies said its application
to move the Johannesburg Stock Exchange’s main board has been
approved by the bourse.  Investec Ltd.  (INL SJ), the private bank and wealth manager
listed in Johannesburg and London, advanced 27 cents, or 0.5
percent, to 59.15 rand. First-half profit through September
climbed 38 percent to 247 million pounds ($393 million).  Keaton Energy Holdings Ltd . (KEH SJ), a South African coal
mining company, reached the highest since Oct. 15, gaining 20
cents, or 4.6 percent, to 4.55 rand. Keaton renewed a notice in
which it said it is in discussions that may affect its price.  SABMiller Plc  (SAB SJ), the world’s second-largest maker of
beer, surged 8.75 rand, or 3.8 percent, to 239.75 rand, the
highest since at least January 1995. SABMiller reported a 19
percent increase in earnings after one-time items to $1.47
billion in the six months through September.  Spar Group Ltd.  (SPP SJ), a South African food and liquor
retailer, rallied to the highest level since its shares started
trading in October 2004, climbing 1.10 rand, or 1.1 percent to
100 rand. The stock’s recommendation was increased to “hold”
from “sell” at Investec Ltd. by equity analyst  Kirsty Laschinger .  Woolworths Holdings Ltd.  (WHL SJ), a South African food and
clothing retailer, slipped 46 cents, or 1.6 percent, to 28 rand,
the lowest closing price since Nov. 9. The group said its
Country Road stores in Australia have been negatively affected
“tough retail conditions” in that country.  To contact the reporter on this story:
